Slide 16: Comparative Analysis: Performance KPIs

SQN: Hit rate improved to 1 in 30; zero fraud in specific bank case studies.

Mitek: 80% hit rate; $16M loss avoidance in 5 months; Day Zero protection.
+2

Fiserv: 50-70% reduction in manual review queues; <120 day deployment.
+1

Parascript: 98-99% accuracy; 70-80% auto-verification rate; 100+ signatures/sec.
+1

Slide 17: Model Interpretability Comparison

SQN: Side-by-side visual display for analysts.


Mitek: MiControl dashboard with visual bounding boxes explaining flags (e.g., "Mismatched Font").


Fiserv: Color-coded bounding boxes and reason codes (e.g., "Signature Variance").
+1


Parascript: "Glass Box" vector analysis; explains failure based on specific graphemes (e.g., "Loop structure inconsistent").

Slide 18: System Weaknesses

SQN: Offline verification struggles with highly skilled tracings.


Mitek: Cloud dependency and potential "Black Box" complexity of deep learning scores.


Fiserv: Legacy image engines may be less effective against deepfakes compared to AI-first vendors.
+1


Parascript: High integration complexity as an SDK/API; requires significant engineering effort.

Slide 19: Strategic Recommendations

For High-Speed Batch/Core Integration: Choose Fiserv for its native ecosystem and "Whole Check" forensics.
+1


For Forensic Precision (Elections/High Value): Choose Parascript for its superior vector-based stroke analysis.
+3


For Mobile-First/Document Integrity: Choose Mitek for its cloud intelligence and image forensics.
+1


For Fraud Team Efficiency: Choose SQN for its proven ability to triage obvious matches and reduce false positives.
+3

Slide 20: Conclusion
Modern ASV has evolved into a multi-layered defense combining biometrics, document forensics, and shared consortium data.
+4

The choice of system depends on the institution’s priority: operational efficiency, ease of integration, or forensic-level accuracy.
